I"∑<p>While paragraphs and lists are meant to identify whole <strong>blocks</strong> of text, we sometimes want to provide meaning to a word (or a few words) <em>within</em> a text.</p>

<h3 id="strong">Strong</h3>

<p>For <strong>important</strong> words, use the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;strong&gt;</code> tag:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
  This is <span class="nt">&lt;strong&gt;</span>important<span class="nt">&lt;/strong&gt;</span> but this is not.
<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<div class="result">
  <p>
    This is <strong>important</strong> but this is not.
  </p>
</div>

<p>By default, <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;strong&gt;</code> elements are displayed in <strong>bold</strong>, but keep in mind that it is only the browser‚Äôs default behavior. Don‚Äôt use <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;strong&gt;</code> <em>only</em> to put some text in bold, but rather to give it more <strong>importance</strong>.</p>

<h3 id="emphasis">Emphasis</h3>

<p>For <em>emphasized</em> words, use the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;em&gt;</code> tag:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
  This is <span class="nt">&lt;em&gt;</span>emphasized<span class="nt">&lt;/em&gt;</span> but this is not.
<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<div class="result">
  <p>
    This is <em>emphasized</em> but this is not.
  </p>
</div>

<p>By default, <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;em&gt;</code> elements are displayed in <em>italic</em>, but keep in mind that it is only the browser‚Äôs default behavior. Don‚Äôt use <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;em&gt;</code> <em>only</em> to put some text in italic, but rather to give it <em>stress emphasis</em>.</p>

<h3 id="abbreviations">Abbreviations</h3>

<p>Abbreviations like <abbr title="World Wide Web Consortium">W3C</abbr> or <abbr title="Compact Disc">CD</abbr> can use the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;abbr&gt;</code> element:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
  I just bought a <span class="nt">&lt;abbr&gt;</span><abbr title="Compact Disc">CD</abbr><span class="nt">&lt;/abbr&gt;</span>.
<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>You can add a <code class="highlighter-rouge">title</code> <strong>attribute</strong> to specify the abbreviation‚Äôs description, which will appear by hovering the element:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
  I just bought a <span class="nt">&lt;abbr</span> <span class="na">title=</span><span class="s">"Compact Disc"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span><abbr title="Compact Disc">CD</abbr><span class="nt">&lt;/abbr&gt;</span>.
<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<div class="result">
  <p>
    I just bought a <abbr title="Compact Disc"><abbr title="Compact Disc">CD</abbr></abbr>.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 id="inline-quotes">Inline quotes</h3>

<p>The <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;blockquote&gt;</code> element is a <strong>block-level</strong> element. It has an <strong>inline</strong> version: <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;q&gt;</code>:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html"><span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
  He said <span class="nt">&lt;q&gt;</span>‚ÄúHello World‚Äù<span class="nt">&lt;/q&gt;</span> and just left.
<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<div class="result">
  <p>
    He said <q>‚ÄúHello World‚Äù</q> and just left.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 id="other-inline-elements">Other inline elements</h3>

<p>There are plenty of other <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/HTML/Element#Inline_text_semantics">inline semantic elements</a> to choose from, but we‚Äôve covered the most common ones.</p>

